  "prompt": "What are the best small classes for freshmen at Southern Connecticut State?",
  "response": "Southern Connecticut State University (SCSU) offers a variety of small classes that can be beneficial for freshmen. Here are some recommendations based on common freshman interests and course sizes:\n\n1. **First-Year Experience (FYE) Courses:**\n   - **UNV 101: First-Year Experience**\n     - A small class designed to help freshmen transition to college life, develop academic skills, and build a support network.\n   - **UNV 102: Freshman Seminar**\n     - Focuses on specific topics or themes to engage students in meaningful discussions and activities.\n\n2. **Core Liberal Arts and Sciences Courses:**\n   - **ENG 110: College Writing**\n     - A foundational course in writing and critical thinking, often offered in smaller sections.\n   - **ENG 112: Writing Arguments**\n     - Builds on ENG 110 and focuses on argumentative writing, usually in smaller class settings.\n\n3. **Introductory Major-Specific Courses:**\n   - **BIO 102: Biology I**\n     - An introductory course for biology majors, often with lab components that keep class sizes smaller.\n   - **PSY 100: Introduction to Psychology**\n     - A foundational course for psychology majors, typically offered in smaller sections to facilitate discussion and engagement.\n\n4. **Electives and Interest-Based Courses:**\n   - **ART 110: Introduction to Visual Arts**\n     - A smaller class size that introduces students to the basics of art appreciation and creation.\n   - **PHI 100: Introduction to Philosophy**\n     - A small class that explores fundamental philosophical questions and theories.\n\n5. **Interdisciplinary Courses:**\n   - **IDS 100: Introduction to Interdisciplinary Studies**\n     - A course that encourages students to think across disciplines, often in smaller settings that promote discussion and collaboration.\n\nWhen selecting courses, consider the following tips:\n\n- **Check Class Sizes:** Look for courses with lower enrollment numbers. You can usually find this information in the course catalog or by speaking with your academic advisor.\n- **Engage with Professors:** Smaller classes offer more opportunities for interaction with professors, which can enhance your learning experience.\n- **Seek Recommendations:** Talk to current students or your advisor about which professors are known for engaging small classes.\n\nRemember, the best class for you will depend on your interests, major, and academic goals. Always consult with your academic advisor to ensure you're making the most of your freshman year at SCSU.",
